{"topicId":"scalar-vector-fields","mnemonics":[{"id":"m-1","title":"Gradient Points Uphill","content":"Gradient (∇f) always points in the direction of steepest increase - like a compass pointing uphill to the peak. The magnitude tells you how steep."},{"id":"m-2","title":"Divergence = Out, Curl = Spin","content":"Divergence (∇·F) measures if vectors point OUT from a point (source/sink). Curl (∇×F) measures if vectors SPIN around a point (rotation). D-I-V-E-R-G-E-N-C-E: Divergence Is Vector Emergence from General Negative to Positive Flow; C-U-R-L: Curl Understands Rotational Loops."},{"id":"m-3","title":"Scalar = Value, Vector = Arrow","content":"Scalar fields: single number at each point (temperature, height). Vector fields: arrow at each point (velocity, force). S = Single, V = Velocity."},{"id":"m-4","title":"Laplacian is Divergence of Gradient","content":"∇²f = ∇·(∇f) - the Laplacian measures how the gradient of a field diverges. Think: second derivative generalized to multiple dimensions."}],"acronyms":[{"term":"∇ (Del)","expansion":"Nabla/Del Operator","usage":"The vector differential operator ∇ = (∂/∂x, ∂/∂y, ∂/∂z) used in gradient, divergence, and curl operations."},{"term":"SFD","expansion":"Scalar Field","usage":"Assigns one scalar value to each point in space - e.g., temperature T(x,y,z) = 25."},{"term":"VFD","expansion":"Vector Field","usage":"Assigns a vector to each point in space - e.g., velocity V(x,y) = (vx, vy)."},{"term":"GOD","expansion":"Gradient Of Divergence","usage":"Mnemonic for operation order: Gradient operates on scalar, Divergence on vector. Not a valid operation in standard calculus."}],"visualTips":[{"concept":"Scalar Field Visualization","visualization":"Use a heat map or topographic contour map. Colors (red=hot, blue=cold) or elevation lines show scalar values. Each point has ONE value."},{"concept":"Vector Field Visualization","visualization":"Draw arrows everywhere. Arrow direction = vector direction, arrow length = magnitude. Weather maps showing wind arrows are classic examples."},{"concept":"Gradient Visualization","visualization":"Imagine contour lines on a mountain. Gradient arrows point PERPENDICULAR to contours, pointing directly uphill. Arrows are longest on steepest slopes."},{"concept":"Divergence Visualization","visualization":"Draw arrows pointing OUT from a center point (positive divergence = source). Draw arrows pointing IN (negative divergence = sink). Like a fountain or drain."},{"concept":"Curl Visualization","visualization":"Draw arrows swirling around a point like a whirlpool. Curl measures the "spinning" tendency. Use the right-hand rule: curl thumb points axis of rotation."}],"analogies":[{"concept":"Scalar Field as Elevation Map","analogy":"A scalar field is like a topographic map of a mountain. Each location has ONE elevation value. You can draw contour lines connecting equal heights."},{"concept":"Vector Field as Water Flow","analogy":"A vector field is like a river current. At every point in the river, water has a direction and speed (the vector). Some areas flow faster (larger arrows), some eddy and curl."},{"concept":"Gradient as Hiker Seeking Peak","analogy":"The gradient is like a hiker who always walks in the steepest uphill direction. The gradient vector points the way to climb fastest - used in gradient descent algorithms."},{"concept":"Divergence as Source or Sink","analogy":"Divergence is like measuring if water is appearing from nowhere (positive/source) or disappearing (negative/sink). A faucet adds water (positive divergence); a drain removes it (negative)."},{"concept":"Curl as Merry-Go-Round","analogy":"Curl measures rotation. Think of a merry-go-round: vectors at different points all circle around the center. High curl = fast spinning, zero curl = no rotation (even if moving)."}]}